eanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Aldo, Caesar.","Italian: habitational name for someone from Carnago in Varese province, Lombardy. This is a typical Lombardic surname; there surnames derived from placenames usually have a pluralized form."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Don","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Donald .  It is also a variant of the Irish name Donn ."],"variants":[{"name":"Donn","meanings":["Ancient byname meaning either ‘brown’ or ‘chief, noble’, in use from the earliest times until the 19th century."]},{"name":"Donald","meanings":["Anglicized form of Gaelic Domhnall . The final <i>-d</i> of the Anglicized form derives partly from misinterpretation by English speakers of the Gaelic pronunciation, and partly from association with Germanic-origin names such as   Ronald .  This name is strongly associated with clan Macdonald, the clan of the medieval Lords of the Isles, but is now also widely used by families with no Scottish connections."]}]},{"name":"Michele","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine form of <i>Michel</i> (  see  Michael  ), also used in the English-speaking world (with or without the accent)."],"variants":[{"name":"Michel","meanings":["Biblical.  See  <b>Michael</b>   ."]},{"name":"Michael","meanings":["form of a common biblical name (meaning ‘who is like God?’ in Hebrew) borne by one of the archangels, the protector of the ancient Hebrews, who is also regarded as a saint of the Catholic Church. In the Middle Ages, Michael was regarded as captain of the heavenly host (see Revelation 12:7–9), symbol of the Church Militant, and patron of soldiers. He was often depicted bearing a flaming sword. The name is also borne by a Persian prince and ally of Belshazzar mentioned in the Book of Daniel. Since the early 1900s it has been one of the m